<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-342-728  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 342 728.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  June 12 1989 v6 n23 p63(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Insurers hold out ray of hope on viruses. (computer viruses)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Scheier, Robert L.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer VirusesInsurance IndustryInsurance Policy Handling.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Insurers Hold OutandM;Ray of Hope on VirusesandM;Does your corporate data-processing insurance policy cover computer viruses?andM;It just might, according to software-industry specialist John Lamberson withthe New York-based insurance brokerage firm of Corroon andamp; Black Corp.andM;It is standard policy in the insurance industry for policies to cover allrisks, unless they're specifically excluded -- and computer viruses often arenot.andM;However, it's unclear whether insurers will pay for the revenue lost due to adata blackout, instead of just the cost of repairing or replacing the data.andM;The majority of current insurance policies don't cover viruses or &quot;worms&quot;that don't actually destroy data, but rather just slow or stop work.andM;Look for insurance companies to devise new approaches to dealing with thevirus threat, Lamberson predicted.andP;  In the meantime, he advised that the bestcure for a virus is still prevention.andM;-- Compiled by Robert L. Scheier</TEXT></DOC>